```julia
function timezone_bumper(dt::DateTime, bump::Int = 3)
    if isa(dt, Date)
        throw(ArgumentError("Cannot adjust date without a time component; use a DateTime instead"))
    end
    return DateTime(dt.year, dt.month, dt.day, dt.hour + bump, dt.minute, dt.second, dt.millisecond, dt.utcoffset)
end
```

This function checks if the input `dt` is a `Date` type and throws an error if so, as Date types do not have a time component and thus cannot be adjusted by hours. If the input is a `DateTime`, it creates a new `DateTime` object with the same year, month, day, and microsecond components as the original, but with the hour increased by `bump` hours. The default value for `bump` is 3 hours.
